# Security Review — `app.js`

> Reviewed: 2026-04-26 | Framework: Express.js | OWASP Top 10 (2021) mapped

---

## Summary

The file is a minimal Express server with two routes. While it is short, it has **several concrete vulnerabilities and missing defences** that would be serious in any real deployment. The findings below are ordered by severity.

---

## 🔴 Critical

### 1. Broken Access Control — Unauthenticated `/users` Endpoint (OWASP A01)

The `/users` route returns user PII (names and emails) to **any caller with no authentication or authorisation check**.

```js
// ❌ Current — anyone on the network can call this
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Fix:** Add an authentication middleware. A minimal JWT example:

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });

  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }
}

// ✅ Protected
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

### 2. Sensitive Data Exposure in Response (OWASP A02)

Even with auth added, the endpoint returns **raw email addresses**. Data minimisation is a GDPR/privacy requirement and reduces blast radius if the endpoint is ever abused.

```js
// ✅ Return only what the caller needs
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const safeUsers = users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })); // omit email
  res.json(safeUsers);
});
```

---

## 🟠 High

### 3. Missing Security Headers (OWASP A05)

No security-relevant HTTP headers are set. This exposes the app to clickjacking, MIME-type sniffing, and XSS via reflected content.

**Fix:** Add [`helmet`](https://helmetjs.github.io/) as the very first middleware:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // sets X-Frame-Options, CSP, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.
```

---

### 4. No Rate Limiting (OWASP A04 / DoS)

All endpoints are unthrottled. An attacker can enumerate data or exhaust server resources with trivial scripting.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per IP per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

app.use(limiter); // apply globally before routes
```

---

### 5. Information Disclosure via `/health` (OWASP A05)

The health endpoint returns a **precise server timestamp**. While low severity alone, precise timing leaks can aid fingerprinting and timing attacks against other endpoints.

```js
// ❌ Exposes precise server time
res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });

// ✅ Return only what load-balancers actually need
res.json({ status: 'ok' });
```

---

### 6. No Global Error Handler (OWASP A05)

Unhandled errors will cause Express to emit a default stack trace in the response body, leaking internal file paths, framework versions, and logic details.

```js
// ✅ Add AFTER all routes, before app.listen()
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log internally
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' }); // never leak details
});
```

---

## 🟡 Medium

### 7. No CORS Policy (OWASP A01)

No CORS headers are set, which means browsers default to same-origin, but the policy is implicit and could be misconfigured later. Explicit is safer:

```js
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN, // e.g. 'https://yourfrontend.com'
  methods: ['GET'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Authorization', 'Content-Type'],
}));
```

---

### 8. No Request Logging / Audit Trail (OWASP A09)

There is no logging of who called what and when. Without this, incident response and intrusion detection are blind.

```js
const morgan = require('morgan');

// 'combined' format includes IP, method, path, status, user-agent
app.use(morgan('combined'));
```

For production, pipe logs to a SIEM or log aggregation service rather than stdout.

---

### 9. Hardcoded Port — No Environment Configuration

The port `3000` is hardcoded. In real deployments this prevents flexible orchestration and can conflict with other services.

```js
// ✅ Use env var with a sensible fallback
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

---

### 10. No Body Parser with Size Limit (OWASP A04 — future risk)

There is currently no `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` middleware. The moment POST routes are added, the app will be vulnerable to oversized payload attacks if a size limit isn't set.

Add it now with a cap:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

## 🔵 Low / Informational

| # | Finding | Recommendation |
|---|---------|---------------|
| 11 | No HTTPS enforcement | Add HSTS header (via `helmet`) or terminate TLS at load balancer; redirect HTTP → HTTPS |
| 12 | `/users` has no pagination | Add `limit`/`offset` query params with server-enforced caps to prevent full-table dumps |
| 13 | Static hardcoded user data | When replaced with a DB query, use parameterised queries to prevent SQL/NoSQL injection (OWASP A03) |
| 14 | No `X-Request-ID` tracing | Add a request-ID header to correlate log entries with responses |

---

